Breast Cancer Prediction Term Project¶

Our dataset describe 30 different characteristics of breast mass which are calculated in 3-dimentional space.[K. P. Bennett and O. L. Mangasarian: "Robust Linear Programming Discrimination of Two Linearly Inseparable Sets", Optimization Methods and Software 1, 1992, 23-34].

As an initial step, 10 different parameter were determined as a basis of measurement for diognosis which can be found with their explanations below, after that with these base parameters 30 different feature were created to include any predictive model.

Attribute Information:¶

1) ID number

2) Diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign)

3-32)

Ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus:¶

a) radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)

b) texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)

c) perimeter

d) area

e) smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)

f) compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)

g) concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)

h) concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)

i) symmetry

j) fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

Model Selection According to Cross Validation Score¶

The purpose of the function we define below is to measure the accuracy of predictions in train and test sets individually when different models are fitted to our train set. It is also examining the cross validation scores to be sure about if we are obtaining the same accuracy for every split of the data.

In [261]:

In [266]:

In [267]:
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
In [268]:
def classification_model(model,trainset,testset,predictors, outcome):
        
        model.fit(trainset[predictors],trainset[outcome])
        
        trainset_predictions = model.predict(trainset[predictors])
        
        trainset_accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(trainset_predictions,trainset[outcome])        
        
        print("Trainset Accuracy : %s" % "{0:.3%}".format(trainset_accuracy))
        
        print("Trainset Cross Validation Scores : ",cross_val_score(model, trainset[predictors], trainset[outcome], cv=5))        
        
        testset_predictions = model.predict(testset[predictors])
        
        testset_accuracy = metrics.accuracy_score(testset_predictions,testset[outcome])        
        
        print("Testset Accuracy : %s" % "{0:.3%}".format(testset_accuracy))
         
        print("Testset Cross Validation Scores : ",cross_val_score(model, testset[predictors], testset[outcome], cv=5))

Individual Contribution Of Each Feature¶

The purpose of the algorithm created in this section is to measure the individual contribution of each feature to model.

In [296]:
acc_list = []

pre_list = []

rec_list = []

for i in range(0,25):
        
    clf_rf_2 = RandomForestClassifier()      

    clf_rf_2.fit(pd.DataFrame(x_train.iloc[:,i]),y_train)
    
    ac_2 = accuracy_score(y_test,clf_rf_2.predict(pd.DataFrame(x_test.iloc[:,i])))
    
    pre = precision_score(y_test,clf_rf_2.predict(pd.DataFrame(x_test.iloc[:,i])))
    
    rec = recall_score(y_test,clf_rf_2.predict(pd.DataFrame(x_test.iloc[:,i])))
    
    acc_list.append(ac_2)
    
    pre_list.append(pre)
    
    rec_list.append(rec)

21 concavity_worst 0.748538 0.758065 0.626667
22 concave points_worst 0.871345 0.863014 0.840000
23 symmetry_worst 0.660819 0.630769 0.546667
24 fractal_dimension_worst 0.649123 0.627119 0.493333

As seen in the table above, although many features give an average accuracy score but their precision and recall values observed lower.

In the model we created, false positive or false negative values are also important.These values should be kept as low as possible.Because otherwise, someone who does not have cancer can be diagnosed with cancer or cells with cancer can be missed.

For this reason, features that create a low recall or precision value can be eliminated.
